<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-355-676  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 355 676.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Networking Management  June 1989 v7 n6 p43(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber opens door to avalanche of applications. (fiber optics)(Includes related article on FDDI)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Axner, David H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic technology, which represents the transmission of databy guiding light impulses through a clear, solid fiber core, isentering an increasing number of applications.andP;  Advantages offiber optics include immunity from interference, data integrity,secure transmission, light weight, and safety in hazardousenvironments.andP;  Many vendors are using fiber optics in local-areanetwork components such as interfaces and bridges.andP;  Thefiber-optics industry is seeking standardization through the FiberDistributed Data Interface (FDDI) system and through theSynchronous Optical Network (SONET) transport developed byBellcore.andP;  FDDI is will be finalized by ANSI this year.andP;  SONET issupported by the North American telephone industry and will allowtransfer of multiplexed T3 signals among different equipment.andO;Methods of interconnecting FDDI and SONET networks are underdevelopment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksConnectivityFiber OpticsFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardApplicationsData Transfer Rate.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Selected fiber-optic multiplexers (table)Selected fiber-optic modems (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>